====Noun====
{{en-noun}}

# The opening part ([[casement]]) of a [[window]] usually containing the [[glass]] [[panes]], hinged to the [[jamb]], or sliding up and down as in a [[sash window]].
#* '''1722''', {{w|Daniel Defoe}}, ''{{w|The Fortunes and Misfortunes of Moll Flanders}},'' London: W. Chetwood and T. Edling, p.{{nbsp}}91,<sup>[http://name.umdl.umich.edu/004843555.0001.000]</sup>
#*: One Morning he pulls off his Diamond Ring, and writes upon the Glass of the '''Sash''' in my Chamber this Line, You I Love, and you alone.
#* '''1823''', {{w|Clement Clarke Moore}}, “{{w|A Visit from St. Nicholas|Account of a Visit from St. Nicholas}}” (“The Night before Christmas”),<sup>[https://en.wikisource.org/wiki/Troy_Sentinel/1823/12/23/Account_of_a_Visit_from_St._Nicholas]</sup>
#*: Away to the window I flew like a flash,
#*: Tore open the shutters, and threw up the '''sash'''.
#*{{RQ:Melville Moby-Dick|chapter=2|page=10|passage="In judging of that tempestuous wind called Euroclydon,” says an old writer—of whose works I possess the only copy extant—“it maketh a marvellous difference, whether thou lookest out at it from a glass window where the frost is all on the outside, or whether thou observest it from that '''sashless''' window, where the frost is on both sides, and of which the wight Death is the only glazier."}}
#* '''1908''', {{w|Arnold Bennett}}, ''{{w|The Old Wives' Tale|The Old Wives’ Tale}},'' Book{{nbsp}}4, Chapter{{nbsp}}2,<sup>[http://www.gutenberg.org/files/5247/5247-h/5247-h.htm]</sup>
#*: She chiefly recalled the Square under snow; cold mornings, and the coldness of the oil-cloth at the window, and the draught of cold air through the ill-fitting '''sash''' (it was put right now)!
# {{lb|en|software|graphical user interface}} A draggable [[vertical]] or [[horizontal]] bar used to adjust the relative sizes of two [[adjacent]] [[window]]s.
#: {{syn|en|splitter}}
# In a [[sawmill]], the [[rectangular]] [[frame]] in which the [[saw]] is [[strain]]ed and by which it is carried up and down with a reciprocating motion; the [[gate]].

